"990–ABT 1055":"0990–about 1055","0990–1055":"0990–1055","0990–1066":"0990–1066","1019–Female":"1019–Deceased","1020–1086":"1020–1086","1022–Male":"1022–Deceased","0968–1035":"0968–1035","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","1010":"1010","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","Abt 1019":"about 1019","990":"0990","1019":"1019","ABT 1055":"about 1055","1035":"1035","0990":"0990","about 1020":"about 1020","0968":"0968","about 1022":"about 1022","Coezou, Morbihan, Bretagne, France":"Morbihan, Brittany, France","Saint-Pol-de-Léon, Finistère, Bretagne, France":"Saint-Pol-de-Léon, Finistère, Brittany, France","France":"France","Quimper, Finistère, Brittany, France":"Quimper, Finistère, Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ou","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Wealthy’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Salomé","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of an unrecorded Aramaic name, akin to the Hebrew word <i>shalom</i> ‘peace’. It was common at the time of Christ, and was borne by one of the women who were at his tomb and witnessed the Resurrection (Mark 16:1–8). This would normally have led to its common use as a Christian name, and it is indeed found as such in medieval times. However, according to the Jewish historian Josephus, it was also the name of King Herod's stepdaughter, the daughter of Queen Herodias. In the Bible, a daughter of Herodias, generally identified as this Salome, danced for Herod and so pleased him that he offered to give her anything she wanted. Prompted by her mother, she asked for (and got) the head of John the Baptist, who was in one of Herod's prisons (Mark 6:17–28). This story so gripped medieval imagination that the name Salome became more or less taboo until the end of the 19th century, when  Oscar Wilde  wrote a play about her and some unconventional souls began to choose the name for their daughters."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marie ou Salomé de COUEZOU was born in 0990, in Morbihan, Brittany, France as the daughter of Rivelin De Coëzou. She married Count Morvan de Leon II in 1010. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died about 1055, in Quimper, Finistère, Brittany, France, at the age of 66."},"et":{"990–ABT 1055":"0990–umbes 1055","0990–1055":"0990–1055","0990–1066":"0990–1066","1019–Female":"1019–Surnud","1020–1086":"1020–1086","1022–Male":"1022–Surnud","0968–1035":"0968–1035","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","1010":"1010","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","Abt 1019":"umbes 1019","990":"0990","1019":"1019","ABT 1055":"um